Ravi Sharma, a 42-year-old male undergoing radiotherapy for head and neck cancer, presents for follow-up care focusing on managing mucositis, fatigue, and dermatitis symptoms. Tamil language and social support needs are integrated into his care plan.  
 
<CHIEF_COMPLAINT>  
Mouth sores, dryness, fatigue, and skin reactions related to ongoing radiotherapy.  
 
<HISTORY_OF_PRESENT_ILLNESS>  
Symptoms started two weeks ago after initiating radiotherapy and include dry mouth with burning, altered taste, reduced appetite, and left neck lump. Fatigue worsens post meals but improves with rest.  
 
<SOCIAL_HISTORY_AND_RISK_FACTORS>  
Patient resides with his sister Priya, who aids in care and translation. Additional support for transportation and materials in Tamil was requested. No smoking or alcohol use reported.  
 
<EXAMINATION_INVESTIGATIONS_AND_PLAN>  
Oral exam and neck evaluation planned with biopsy only if suspicious findings are noted. Nutritional advice includes high-protein, soft foods (dal, eggs, yogurt). Oral hygiene measures involve saltwater rinses and lip moisturization. Social worker will assist with transport and subsidies. Follow-up in two weeks with potential lab tests or imaging if required.  
 
<SAFETY_AND_RED_FLAGS>  
Patient is advised to monitor for signs of infection (fever >38°C, redness, swelling, foul odor) and uncontrolled symptoms (pain or dehydration). A 24/7 nurse and on-call support are available for urgent issues.  
 
<OVERALL_SUMMARY>  
Ravi Sharma, undergoing radiotherapy, is managing side effects like dry mouth, fatigue, and a left neck lump. A comprehensive care plan includes symptom management, nutritional guidance, and close monitoring. Tamil language resources, transport assistance, and a two-week follow-up are arranged to address biopsies and ensure continued treatment without interruptions.
